# JWT Authentication System — Implementation Plan

## Context

The Express API currently has no authentication. All POST/PUT/DELETE endpoints accept a `userId` from the request body with no verification. The task is to add a full JWT-based auth system: registration, login, token issuance, protected routes, and ownership enforcement. The `jsonwebtoken` library is already installed. All new behavior is already spec'd in `tests/auth.test.ts`.

---

## Critical Files

| File | Action |
|---|---|
| `src/routes/auth.ts` | **Create** — register & login endpoints |
| `src/middleware/auth.ts` | **Create** — JWT verification middleware |
| `src/routes/posts.ts` | **Modify** — protect POST/PUT/DELETE, enforce ownership |
| `src/routes/comments.ts` | **Modify** — protect POST/PUT/DELETE, enforce ownership |
| `src/types.ts` | **Modify** — extend Express `Request` with `user` field |
| `src/app.ts` | **Modify** — register auth router |

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — Extend `src/types.ts`

Add a global Express Request augmentation so `req.user` is typed everywhere. Append to the end of the file:

```ts
declare global {
  namespace Express {
    interface Request {
      user?: { id: number; username: string };
    }
  }
}
```

---

### Step 2 — Create `src/middleware/auth.ts`

```ts
import { Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";

const JWT_SECRET = "super-secret-key";

export { JWT_SECRET };

export function authenticate(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction): void {
  const authHeader = req.headers.authorization;
  if (!authHeader || !authHeader.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Authorization token required" });
    return;
  }
  const token = authHeader.split(" ")[1];
  try {
    const payload = jwt.verify(token, JWT_SECRET) as { id: number; username: string };
    req.user = payload;
    next();
  } catch {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid or expired token" });
  }
}
```

**Key decisions:**
- Exports `JWT_SECRET` so `auth.ts` routes can reuse the same constant.
- Returns `401` (not `403`) on missing/invalid tokens, matching the test expectations.
- Casts the JWT payload to `{ id, username }` — this matches the shape we put in on sign.

---

### Step 3 — Create `src/routes/auth.ts`

Uses Node's built-in `crypto.createHash("sha256")` for password hashing (no bcrypt needed, as specified).

```ts
import { Router } from "express";
import { createHash } from "crypto";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";
import { users, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { JWT_SECRET } from "../middleware/auth.js";

const router = Router();

function hashPassword(password: string): string {
  return createHash("sha256").update(password).digest("hex");
}

// POST /auth/register
router.post("/register", (req, res) => {
  const { username, email, password } = req.body;
  if (!username || !email || !password) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "username, email, and password are required" });
    return;
  }
  if (users.find((u) => u.username === username)) {
    res.status(409).json({ error: "Username already taken" });
    return;
  }
  const newUser = {
    id: nextId(users),
    username,
    email,
    password: hashPassword(password),
  };
  users.push(newUser);
  const token = jwt.sign({ id: newUser.id, username: newUser.username }, JWT_SECRET);
  const { password: _, ...userWithoutPassword } = newUser;
  res.status(201).json({ token, user: userWithoutPassword });
});

// POST /auth/login
router.post("/login", (req, res) => {
  const { username, password } = req.body;
  const user = users.find((u) => u.username === username);
  if (!user || user.password !== hashPassword(password)) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid credentials" });
    return;
  }
  const token = jwt.sign({ id: user.id, username: user.username }, JWT_SECRET);
  res.json({ token });
});

export { router as authRouter };
```

**Key decisions:**
- Password comparison uses the same `hashPassword` function, so register → login round-trips correctly.
- Seed users in `db.ts` have plaintext passwords. This is fine because no test logs in as a seed user — auth tests always register fresh users first.
- The `user` response object uses destructuring to omit `password` (tests verify it's absent).
- JWT payload: `{ id, username }` — matches what `authenticate` middleware expects to read back.
- No `expiresIn` added to keep things simple; tests don't test expiry.

---

### Step 4 — Modify `src/routes/posts.ts`

- Import `authenticate` from `../middleware/auth.js`
- Apply `authenticate` as middleware on POST, PUT, DELETE
- POST: set `userId` from `req.user!.id` (not body)
- PUT: check `post.userId === req.user!.id`, return 403 if mismatch
- DELETE: check `post.userId === req.user!.id`, return 403 if mismatch

```ts
import { Router } from "express";
import { posts, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { Post } from "../types.js";
import { authenticate } from "../middleware/auth.js";

const router = Router();

// GET /posts  (public)
router.get("/", (req, res) => { ... });

// GET /posts/:id  (public)
router.get("/:id", (req, res) => { ... });

// POST /posts  (protected)
router.post("/", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (!title || !content) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "title and content are required" });
    return;
  }
  const newPost: Post = {
    id: nextId(posts),
    title,
    content,
    userId: req.user!.id,          // ← from token, not body
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  posts.push(newPost);
  res.status(201).json(newPost);
});

// PUT /posts/:id  (protected + ownership)
router.put("/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.id) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (title) posts[index].title = title;
  if (content) posts[index].content = content;
  res.json(posts[index]);
});

// DELETE /posts/:id  (protected + ownership)
router.delete("/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.id) {
