- The `user` response object uses destructuring to omit `password` (tests verify it's absent).
- JWT payload: `{ id, username }` — matches what `authenticate` middleware expects to read back.
- No `expiresIn` added to keep things simple; tests don't test expiry.

---

### Step 4 — Modify `src/routes/posts.ts`

- Import `authenticate` from `../middleware/auth.js`
- Apply `authenticate` as middleware on POST, PUT, DELETE
- POST: set `userId` from `req.user!.id` (not body)
- PUT: check `post.userId === req.user!.id`, return 403 if mismatch
- DELETE: check `post.userId === req.user!.id`, return 403 if mismatch

```ts
import { Router } from "express";
import { posts, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { Post } from "../types.js";
import { authenticate } from "../middleware/auth.js";

const router = Router();

// GET /posts  (public)
router.get("/", (req, res) => { ... });

// GET /posts/:id  (public)
router.get("/:id", (req, res) => { ... });

// POST /posts  (protected)
router.post("/", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (!title || !content) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "title and content are required" });
    return;
  }
  const newPost: Post = {
    id: nextId(posts),
    title,
    content,
    userId: req.user!.id,          // ← from token, not body
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  posts.push(newPost);
  res.status(201).json(newPost);
});

// PUT /posts/:id  (protected + ownership)
router.put("/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.id) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (title) posts[index].title = title;
  if (content) posts[index].content = content;
  res.json(posts[index]);
});

// DELETE /posts/:id  (protected + ownership)
router.delete("/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.id) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const deleted = posts.splice(index, 1);
  res.json(deleted[0]);
});

export { router as postsRouter };
```

---

### Step 5 — Modify `src/routes/comments.ts`

Same pattern as posts:
- Import `authenticate`
- POST `"/posts/:postId/comments"`: add `authenticate`, set `userId` from `req.user!.id`
- PUT `"/comments/:id"`: add `authenticate`, check ownership → 403 if mismatch
- DELETE `"/comments/:id"`: add `authenticate`, check ownership → 403 if mismatch
- GET routes stay unchanged (public)

---

### Step 6 — Modify `src/app.ts`

Import and mount the auth router:

```ts
import { authRouter } from "./routes/auth.js";

// add before existing route registrations:
app.use("/auth", authRouter);
```

---

## Import Conventions (ESM + Node16)

All local imports must use `.js` extensions (this is the existing pattern throughout the codebase):
- `from "../middleware/auth.js"`
- `from "../db.js"`
- `from "../types.js"`

The `jsonwebtoken` default import works because `"esModuleInterop": true` is set in `tsconfig.json`.

---

## Existing Tests — Why They Stay Green

| Test file | Concern | Resolution |
|---|---|---|
| `posts.test.ts` | Only GETs `/posts`, `/posts/1`, `/health` | GET routes stay public — no auth applied |
| `comments.test.ts` | `GET /posts/1/comments` expects exactly 2 items | GET stays public; vitest runs each file in isolated worker (separate in-memory DB) |
| `comments.test.ts` | `GET /comments/1` checks seed data | Read-only; unaffected |

---

## Verification

```bash
# Run all tests
npm test

# Expected: all tests in posts.test.ts and comments.test.ts pass unchanged
# Expected: all 14 tests in auth.test.ts pass
```

Manual smoke test (after `npm run build && npm start`):
```bash
